If you want to import all the symbols from a package, you can use the `Exporter` module which provides `import` and `export` subroutines to control the export of symbols from packages.

To use `Exporter`, you first need to make your package inherit from the it by adding `use Exporter;` and `our @EXPORT;` to your package code. Then, you can use `@EXPORT` array to list the symbols you want to export, or set it to `@EXPORT_OK` to allow explicit importation of the symbols.

Here is an example code:

```
# MyPackage.pm
package MyPackage;
use Exporter;
our @EXPORT = qw(my_var my_sub);

sub my_var {
    return "Hello, world!";
}

sub my_sub {
    return "I " . my_var();
}

1;
```

When you `use` the package in your code like this:

```
use MyPackage;
print my_var();  # prints "Hello, world!"
print my_sub();  # prints "I Hello, world!"
```

All the symbols listed in the `@EXPORT` array are imported into your code's namespace without having to qualify their names with the package name. In this case, `my_var()` and `my_sub()` are directly available in the importing code's namespace.

Note that exporting all symbols from a package can lead to namespace pollution and potential naming conflicts, so it's generally recommended to use selective exportation using the `@EXPORT_OK` array instead.
